# OSINT Agent

A standalone local research app for accuracy-first open-source intelligence workflows.

## What it does

- Searches the web for relevant material
- Searches the Internet Archive for archived pages and texts
- Follows links from web results and identifies linked PDFs
- Visualizes crawl paths and discovery depth
- Extracts text from local PDF files or PDF URLs
- Ranks sources by evidence strength and relevance
- Produces a report with sources, excerpts, and a confidence-aware summary
- Exports JSON and CSV evidence bundles
 - Learns from saved feedback with a small backprop-trained neural ranker

## Install

```bash
pip install -e .
```

## Run

```bash
osint-agent investigate "target subject" --pdf ./evidence.pdf --archive-limit 10 --web-limit 10 --json-output ./run.json --csv-output ./run.csv
```

By default it uses an allowlist derived from the initial seed domains while crawling. Pass `--open-crawl` if you want it to expand more freely.

You can also pass multiple PDFs:

```bash
osint-agent investigate "target subject" --pdf one.pdf --pdf two.pdf
```

## Notes

This app is designed to gather evidence and organize findings. It does not invent facts, and it surfaces uncertainty instead of hiding it.

Train the learning model from saved feedback:

```bash
osint-agent learn train
```

Run a PHANTOM_LEGION coordinator (optionally persistent):

```bash
osint-agent phantom-coordinator --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8780 --token phantom --db-path .coordinator.db
```

Start a PHANTOM_LEGION worker agent that joins the queue and polls for jobs:

```bash
osint-agent phantom-worker --coordinator-url http://127.0.0.1:8780 --token phantom
```

Dispatch queued work to a coordinator with a pool of workers:

```bash
osint-agent legion "target subject" --coordinator-url http://127.0.0.1:8780 --token phantom
```

The coordinator persists all jobs and worker heartbeats to SQLite, so work survives coordinator restarts. Workers automatically re-join after failure, and claimed jobs are recovered after 10 minutes of inactivity.

Installation notes for PyTorch (required for training/inference):

On most systems the easiest way is to install the CPU wheels from PyTorch's official index. Example (CPU-only):

```bash
pip install torch --index-url https://download.pytorch.org/whl/cpu
```

For GPUs or other configurations, visit https://pytorch.org/get-started/locally/ and follow the recommended command for your platform and CUDA version.
